value.value: The period between stimulus and contraction.

The precise modulations of contractions of the individual muscles. When expressed together or in a specific sequence, these contractions embody the displacements in space that are interpreted as the expression of particular behaviors.

definition.value: Little is known of the functional anatomy of the mosquito nervous system.

value.value: The part of the peripheral nervous system that acts as a control system, maintaining homeostasis in the body.
Arises during embryonic development by an ingrowth from the dorsal wall of the stomodaeum which later requires connexion with the brain.

Innervates the sexual organs and the posterior segments of the gut is composed of nerves arising from the composite terminal ganglion of the abdomen. The mid-gut, the heart and the Malpighian tubes show continued movements after separation from the central nervous system. The control of these movements is attributed to peripheral ganglion cells; and it has been suggested that it is this autonomous peripheral system that should be called the sympathetic nervous system.
The endocrine system is an integrated system of small organs that involve the release of extracellular signaling molecules known as hormones.

definition.value: Consists of: (i) modified nerve cells, (ii) neuro-haemal organs which are believed to serve as the sites at which the neurospecretory products escape into the blood-stream and (iii) independant organs of internal secretion derived from nests of cells which have been budded off the ectoderm in the region of the mouth part.

value.value: The sense by which the qualities of an object (as color, luminosity, shape, and size) constituting its appearance are perceived through a process in which light rays entering the eye are transformed by the retina into electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain via the optic nerve.
Behaviour displayed by mosquitoes that feed on wider range of hosts, while in habitats in which a wide range of potential hosts is present.

The waves of air pressure which we recognize as sounds may be perceived by insects by two quite different mechanism. The antennae of mosquitoes are mechanosensory transducers which in flight respond to drag forces and to gravitational forces, and in which the males at least are also sensitive to sound waves. Organs of hearing convert the energy of sound waves into electrical signals, and in this way resemble microphones.

The perception of the qualities of sweet, sour, salt and bitter. Gustatory sensilla are uniporous hair or peg sensilla that respond to stimulating molecules in the liquid phase. In mosquitoes they are present on the legs and mouthparts, and the input from the various sensilla is intergrated centrally.

The sense of smell in insects is located chiefly in the antennae. The olfactory sensilla of mosquitoes compromise multiporous hair and peg sensilla on the antennal flagella and multiporous peg sensilla on the maxillary palps.

definition.value:
The volitile compounds that have been tested for activity in these sensilla fall into 4 classes:
1) Carbon Dioxide.
2) Unsubstituted and substituded short-chain,aliphatic monocarboxylic acids.
3) Essential oils.
4) Attracttans.

value.value: The process of any action or reaction of a vector organism in response to external or internal stimuli.

It is found that the behavioural activities of adult mosquitoes take place at particular times of day and night, which vary between species and the timing is controlled by endogeous or so-called circadian rythms, which are reset daily by the change from light to dark at sunset.
The analysis of the movements of the mosquito's larva into a series of reflexes or observed correlations between stimulus and response.
The analysis of the movements of the mosquito's pupa into a series of reflexes or observed correlations between stimulus and response.
Any behavioral process during the adult stage of a vector organism.

The circulation of the blood is maintained by a system of muscular pumps and fibro-muscular septa. The haemolymph has many functions. It provides the tissues that it bathes with nutrients and metabolic intermediates, and it provides a medium for the transport of their chemical wastes.
Oragnic material of almost every kind in nature serve as food for insects. The process of nutrition starts with the ingestion of food and ends with the digestion.

definition.value: The reproductive capacity of female mosquitoes is affected by their nutrition in both the larval and adult stages.

value.value: The process of taking a substance into the body through the mouth.
The process with which oxygen is conveyed from the atmosphere to the tissues, and how the carbon dioxide resulting from oxidation in the tissues is eliminated.
The intake of oxygen in the adult mosquito.

Larvae use an open respiratory system which impose limitations to the requirement for access to atmospheric oxygen. The mosquito larval tracheal system consist of two wide dorsal longitydinal trunks, two narrower lateral, and branches which run from them to all regions of the body.

definition.value: A pair of air sacs of unknown function is present near the junction of thorax and abdomen in certain species.

value.value: The 1st abdominal spiracles open into the ventral air space, which is enclosed by the pupal mouthparts, wings and legs and which functions in pupal buoyancy.

definition.value: Mosquito pupae are the only insects that have only the anterior thoracic and the anterior abdominal spiracles functional. Most of the outer surface of the respiratory trumpet is hydrophilic, but the spiracular opening is surrounded by a ring of hydrophobic cuticle against which water forms a contact angle.

value.value: The processes that rid the adult mosquito body of unwanted substances and ensure homeostasis of the hemolymph under conditions of water and salt loading.
The secretion and regulation of inorganic ions in larvae.
All the chemical changes which the constituents of the vector undergo. These changes serve two purposes, growth on the one hand and the performance of the work on the other.
The rate at which processes of oxidation take place in the living body, varies within wide limits.

definition.value: The values recorded depend upon muscular activity, external temperature, tissue growth, and a host of other factors.

value.value: The hormonal involvement in the regulation of enzyme synthesis.

Energy metabolism starts when an insect ingests food, which supplies the fuel from which the chemical energy is liberated. Energy can be gained from lipids, carbohydrates, or proteins, but each one of these compounds cannot be used under every condition. The primary energy stores in insects are the fat body and the haemolymph.

Primarily a mechanism of growth, conditioned by the properties of the cuticle. There are two aspects to the problem of moulting; i) the initiation of the process of the growth and cuticle ii) the determination of those changes in form that occur during ecdysis. Moulting involves all parts of the body, whether supplied with nerves or not, at the same time. Each moult can be considered as a sequence of events.

Little is known of the structure of mosquito larval cuticle other than that the abdomen it consists of a two-layered corrugated epicuticle, a then exocuticle and an endocuticle of some five lamellae. Pore canals are present.

Three hours after larval-pupal ecdysis the epicuticle darkens. The outer seven lamellae of the procuticle which constitute the outer region of exocuticle darken shortly thereafter, and subsequently the epicuticle and outer exocuticle look like a single homogeneous layer. The colour of the pupal abdomen changes from white at ecdysis to grey after one hour and to dark brown after three hours.

Formation of pharate cuticle starts during the later stages of dissolution of the pupal cuticle. Seventeen hours after larval-pupal ecdysis small 3-layered plates are deposited just above the apical membrane of the epidermal cells, which bears minute microvilli at this stage. Addition of material at the edges of the plate leads to the formation of a continuous layer of outer epicuticle over the epidermal cells. By the pupal-adult ecdysis there are four lamellae.
Fifteen hours after larval-pupal ecdysis, apolysis starts. The epidermis separates from the pupal cuticle forming an apolysial space in which a small amount of apolysial fluid accumulates.

The hormone from the neurosecretory cells of the brain activates the thoracic glands and causes them to secrete the moulting hormone. The thoracic glands requie the continued presence of the brain hormone until the "critical period", when mitosis has begun and there is an adequate supply of moulting hormone in the blood.

During moulting, even when unaccompanied by any striking change of form, there is much reconstruction in the epidermis. New cell divisions and the death and disolution of unwanted nuclei take place simultaneously.
A condition in which growth or development is suspended and physiological activity is diminished.

During the first or second day after emergence, a mosquito undergoes behavioural maturation when, due to the action of hormones and other substances that act on the nervous system, it becomes competent in sexual behaviour.

Male mosquitos become sexually responsive to flying conspecific females 12-36h after emergence, by which time their terminalia have inverted and their antennal fibrilae have become either permanenrly erect or capable of temporary erection.

Observations of the coupling of force-mated or tethered females suggested that refractoriness is expressed through altered responses of the female terminalia to genital contact. Even if coupling occurs, it does not result in sperm transfer.
Is a form of foraging, and it includes responses to the environment at three hierarchical levels: the habitat, the patch or biotope, and the resource item.

The pupae of almost all holometabolous insects are incapable of locomotion; instead the mosquito pupae swim and dive exceptionaly. Although they can swim strongly, they spend most of their time immobile at the water surface.

Mosquito larvae have the usual internal organs of ion regulation and also they have four external balloon-like anal papillae, which are capable of ion uptake from very dilute solution. They are anatomically adapted for the specific characteristics of the water surface, notably the surface forces in the air-water interface. Mosquitoes (mostly Culidis) form part of the neuston-the assemblage of small to medium-sized organisms that live at the water surface.

definition.value:
Factors that characterize the water surface: (i)surface tension and (ii)surface film.
Aquatic insects which live immediately under the water surface have access to two major resources:
(i) They can obtain direct access to the atmosphere for respiration.
(ii) They are in the immediate vicinity of food.

value.value: The movements of the larvae that are oriented directly towards or directly away from stimuli. Prefixes denote the nature of the stimulus. A taxis is positive if directed towards the source, and negative if directed away from it.
Unoriented movements made in response to particular stimuli. The strength of the response is related to intensity of stimulation. Kineses can have prefixes that denote the nature of the stimulus.

The characteristic food resource of mosquito larvae is 'particular matter'. This includes aquatic microorganisms, such as bacteria, diatoms and algae, and also, as an important component, particles of detritus that are largely derived from decayed plant tissues.

definition.value:
Divided into three activities:
1)movement to a source of food.
2)capture of food by behaviour appropriate to the food source.
3)Coordination of the intricate mouthparts movements.

value.value: Larvae groom themselves by working their mouthparts over accessible parts of the body surface. After their use in feeding and grooming, the mouthparts themselves need to be cleaned, and structures that serve that function are present at the posterior end of the abdomen of the most larvae.

definition.value: To groom the abdomen, larvae bend themselves into a loop. The body part that is most often cleaned is the spiracular opening of the respiratory siphon.

value.value: Adult mosquitos have two accurate and sensitive compound eyes. They have the capacity to resolve details of the spatial environment and so permit complex activities such as upwind flight and position holding in swarms. The compound eyes of the adult mosquito arise during the first larval instar as thickenings of the epidermis, called optic placodes, just anterior to the stemmata. The compound eyes of the mosquitoes have the capacity to resolve details of the spatial environment and so permit complex activities such as upwind flight and position holding swarms.

definition.value: Much remains to be discovered about connections between optic sensilla or ommatidia with the visual neuropiles in the optic lobes and the information from the neurons.

value.value: Simple structures which differ from the ocelli or single-lens eyes present in the adults of most orders and in the larvae of most non-holometabolous orders of insects.

definition.value: The larval visual organs are stemmata (lateral ocelli).

value.value: Both sexes require plant juices as an energy source. Female mosquitoes imbibe blood to obtain protein for ovary development.

definition.value: Toxorhynchitine females do NOT require blood for oogenesis. They feed only on plant juices.
